Done
Done
Is this logic is going to work MPIPL boot ( before completion) -> another MPIPL Request use case?
Another MPIPL from user is not allowed until host reach standby/running.
refering mpipl by phyp , double fault kind of usecase.

That is mostly like a system initiated MPIPL before notify followed by user initiated MPIPL, in such case the inprogress user initiated MPIPL will get updated after the second MPIPL, I think that is a very rare case.

Anyway two back to back user initiated MPIPLs are covered
Double fault is not impacted, since the entry is not created for system(PHYP) initiated MPIPLs
Ack
All looks good
srcDumpId local variable is removed but it is used here?
Done
we are using status() here and above we are using offloadUri().empty() to check if offload is in progress, do we need to modify line 40 too? just clarification

status says dump creation is in progress or not
offloadURI indicate an offload is in progress
typo
Done
should handle file system exceptions.
Done
in progress?
Done
Incase double fault case TI followed by another TI , how the entry delete works fpor the first one?
I don't think there will be TI followed by a TI because, with the first TI, the host will be down.
It is possible , TI(1) trigger MPIPL , during MPIPL , Phyp initialization window , can trigger another TI , we seen these scenarios mutiple tim e, in phyp got some critical issues.

That TI will be after MPIPL, not in sequence before starting MPIPL,  and in such cases old dump will be lost and a new dump will be created.
another important point is this is applicable only for user initiated dump since a dump entry will not be created in TI case

How about 
- user initiate dump
- TI during early phyp start use case?
this will fail user requested mpipl and with this logic next TI initiated MPIPL will also fail right? am i missing some thing here?

High level this commit seems to be ensuring there is only one active dump during an MPIPL? i.e. you've changed the service do always run now, even during an MPIPL. I'm not sure how it being a user initiated or host initiated makes a difference here? The service will always run and clear any dumps that are not "phosphor::dump::OperationStatus::InProgress"?
yes there is only one possible system dump at a time, need to delete all dump entries during a system power off because those will be stale except the newly created entry which triggered mpipl
ok, can you remove mention of "When the system dump is initiated by user" from commit message. That part seems irrelevant here and confused me.
Done
Still seems to be present in commit msg?
Oh something missed.. will remove

This variable is used in multiple places. mainly in services , openbmc,openpower-proc-control  repos. Usually services uses environment file base approach to use variables. 
@andrewg how this handled in generally by services?
I think now we can reuse dump in progress from settings instead of this file

Yeah, be great to have this only coming from one place within this repo. But in general, this file path is considered an API so it will not be changed (it's hard coded in services). Where things will get confusing is if we some day support multiple host instances (or composed systems). Then there may be a file per instance....but if this code is just running on a single satellite then it's still only in one instance. So... a lot TBD there but for now it's ok to hard code. Wrapping it in a utility function like isInMpReboot() is a good idea so it if it does change we can just change in one place.
is this formating is done manually?
No, but lg2 is not getting formatted properly with clang-16
That's weird formatting. May want to ping Patrick to see if he has any ideas.
replace with e?
Done

To me this used to make a lot more sense. If we're in a mpreboot, don't call DeleteAll. But now, we call DeleteAll, but it actually doesn't delete everything. It goes against the principal of least surprise. Was there a specific bug we're fixing here where there were multiple dumps present? We are almost there now
Originally, during an mpreboot, the DeleteAll function was not executed because we didn't want to delete the user-initiated dump entry. The intention here was to preserve any user-requested dumps.

A defect was identified when old dumps were not deleted as expected if a user requested a new dump while an existing one was present. 

Subsequently, we added code to disallow the initiation of user-requested dumps when one already exists. This effectively ensures that we cannot have more than one dump entry at any given time.

The remaining challenge lies in handling scenarios where an mpreboot fails. If a user had requested a dump and an entry was created, but the mpreboot subsequently fails, that entry will remain. Consequently, if the user requests another dump, we end up with two unfinished entries.

I  think that this issue should be handled separately. One possible solution is to implement a method that marks any in-progress system dump entries as failed during a normal boot. A normal boot is the likely scenario following a failed mpreboot.
